TAILAGE. A piece cut out of the whole;
a share of one’s substance paid by way of
tribute; a toll or tax. Cowell.

TEINLAND. Sax. In old English law.
Land of a thane or Saxon noble; land granted by the crown to a thane or lord. Cowell;
1 Reeve, Eng. Law, 5. .

TERTIUS INTERVENIENS. Lat. In
the civil law. A third person intervening ;
a third person who comes in between the parties to a suit; one who interpleads. Gilbert’s Forum Rom. 47.

TESTABLE. A person is said to be testable when he has capacity to make a will;
a man of twenty-one years of age and of
sane mind is testable.

TILLAGE. A place tilled or cultivated;
land under cultivation, as opposed to lands
lying fallow or in pasture.

TOLTA. In old English law.
rapine; extortion. Cowell.


Wrong;

TRANSCRIPT. An official copy of certain proceedings in a court. Thus, any. person interested in a judgment or other record of a court can obtain a transcript of it.
U. S. v. Gaussen, 19 Wall. 212, 22 L. Ed. 41;
State v. Board of Equalization, 7 Nev. 95;
Hastings School Dist. v. Caldwell, 16 Neb.
68, 19 N. W. 684; Dearborn v. Patton, 4
Or. 61.

TRANSITUS.
Passing from one place to another;
passage, transit, or way.

TRESAEL. L. Fr. A great-great-grandfather. Britt. c. 119. Otherwise written
“tresaiel,” and “tresayle.” 3 Bl. Comm. 186;
Litt. § 20.

TURPITUDO. Lat. Baseness; infamy;
immorality; turpitude.


Tuta est custodia quae sibimet oreditur. Hob. 340. That guardianship is secure which is intrusted to itself alone.
